  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Applying as Startup Without Innovation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The Startup Permit requires genuine innovation and scalability. Traditional consulting, freelancing, or "Uber for X" ideas without clear differentiation get rejected. Business Finland evaluates innovation seriously—this isn't a backdoor for any business.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expired Eligibility Statement</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Business Finland's Eligibility Statement expires after 4 months. If you wait too long to apply for the residence permit, you'll need a new statement. Apply promptly after receiving approval.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting to Freelance Without Permit</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Finland doesn't offer a pure freelancer visa. You can't simply work as a "light entrepreneur" (kevytyrittäjä) without another residence permit basis. You need Startup Permit, Entrepreneur Permit, or other valid permit first.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating Winter</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Finnish winters are dark and cold. Helsinki has ~6 hours daylight in December. Many expats struggle with Seasonal Affective Disorder (SAD). Plan for light therapy, active social life, and winter sports to cope.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">No Finnish Network</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Building business in Finland requires local connections. Finns value trust and long-term relationships. Arrive prepared to network actively—Slush, Maria 01, industry events. Don't expect to succeed working only with foreign clients remotely.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

