  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between Startup and Entrepreneur Permits?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Startup Permit is for innovative, scalable businesses—requires Business Finland approval but offers 2-week processing. Entrepreneur Permit is for established business owners—any profitable self-employment, but requires ELY Centre evaluation (2-4 months). Choose based on whether you have innovation or existing business.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I freelance in Finland?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not directly—there's no pure freelancer visa. You need another residence permit first (startup, entrepreneur, employee, or other). Once you have valid residence, you can do freelance work alongside it. "Light entrepreneurship" (invoicing services) isn't a basis for residence permit.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How fast is the 2-week processing?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          With Business Finland approval, Migri processes Startup Permits in approximately 2 weeks. This is real fast-tracking—one of the quickest business immigration routes in Europe. But getting Business Finland approval first takes 2-4 weeks, so total timeline is about 4-6 weeks.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to speak Finnish?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Not legally required, and Helsinki's tech scene operates largely in English. But Finnish integration improves long-term success—business relationships, daily life, citizenship eligibility (requires language test). English works for startup world; Finnish helps for broader business.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How dark is Finnish winter?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Helsinki: ~6 hours of daylight in December, sun rises ~9am and sets ~3pm. Northern Finland (Lapland) has polar night—sun doesn't rise at all for weeks. Summers compensate with midnight sun. Plan for light therapy, vitamin D, and active social life to handle winter darkness.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the path to permanent residency?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          4 years of continuous residence with valid permit. You must maintain your business and meet permit requirements throughout. After 4 years, apply for permanent residence (P permit). Finnish citizenship requires 5 years residence plus language test (Finnish or Swedish).
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Finland offers one of Europe's fastest business immigration routes—if you qualify. The Startup Permit with Business Finland approval takes just 2 weeks, but requires genuine innovation and scalability. Traditional freelancers without startup concepts need the slower Entrepreneur Permit route.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The Finnish trade-off is clear: high costs and dark winters in exchange for world-class quality of life, excellent startup ecosystem (especially gaming and cleantech), and path to EU citizenship. Finland consistently ranks as the world's happiest country—there's substance behind the reputation.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For tech entrepreneurs with genuinely innovative ideas, Finland deserves serious consideration. The 2-week fast-track, Business Finland support, and strong talent pool make it compelling. For traditional freelancers or remote workers, other EU options may be more appropriate.
    </p>

